        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="0">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The circuit diagram used in this TSI letter is typical. Refer to the Circuit Diagram Book in
                        the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual for the model being serviced.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Batteries expel explosive gases. Keep sparks, flames, burning cigarettes, or other ignition
                        sources away at all times. Alway wear safety glasses and a face shield when working near
                        batteries to prevent personal injury.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the negative cable from the battery terminal.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Locate circuit 70B
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0008061">(Figure 1)</hotlnk>
                    and cut this circuit at a point that will allow the end coming from the stop light switch to be
                    spliced to the relay harness for terminal 86 on the relay
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0008062">(Figure 2)</hotlnk>. The other end of circuit 70B (from the turn signal
                    switch) is spliced to the relay harness for relay terminal 87.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect relay terminal 85 harness lead to ground
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0008062">(Figure 2)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect relay terminal 30 harness lead to fuse F9 with 14 gauge wire
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0008062">(Figure 2)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the relay into the harness connector.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Secure the relay and harness to avoid contact with surfaces that may chafe the harness and
                        cause a circuit to short out.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reconnect the negative cable to the battery.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
        <svcproc svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="3">
            <title>Troubleshooting Guidelines</title>
            <para>The following may cause the brake warning light and buzzer to actuate:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Blown fuses in circuit 90C, fuse F33, or circuit 70, fuse F9. With the ignition key in
                    the off position and the brake pedal depressed, the brake light and back-up pump will come on at the
                    same time.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>If the back-up pump does not come on, check circuit 90C, fuse F33.</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>If the brake light does not come on, check circuit 70, fuse F9.</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The switch contacts on the hydraulic brake switch and the stop light switch are in
                    sequence and must open and close at the same time. Check the status of pins G and H of the hydraulic
                    brake monitor module with the brake pedal depressed. Both pins G and H must have voltage. If only
                    one pin has voltage the brake warning light will activate in 9 to 21 seconds.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Open blocking diodes in connector 48.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loose or intermittent connections or terminals in either the power or ground circuits.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Open or shorted flow switch.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Shorted pressure differential switch.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Open circuit in the booster pump motor. Measure the resistance of the booster pump motor
                    with an ohm meter. The resistance measurement should be less than 100 ohms. Alternately, check the
                    voltage at pin F of the brake monitor module. If the voltage is greater than 2.5 volts, the brake
                    warning light and buzzer will be activated.
                </para>
            </step1>
